### 3.7 CNN / ResNet50 (Medical Image Analysis)

> [!info] What CNN is
> Convolutional Neural Network — a deep learning architecture that excels at image processing. Uses convolutional layers to detect features like edges, textures, shapes.

> [!info] What ResNet50 is
> A 50-layer deep CNN with "residual connections" (skip connections). Solves the vanishing gradient problem by letting gradients flow through skip connections. Pretrained on ImageNet (1.4M images, 1000 classes).

**Why ResNet50 for Care++:**
- Proven architecture for medical imaging
- Deep enough to learn complex features (tumor shapes, anomalies)
- Residual connections prevent training instability
- Transfer learning from ImageNet → fine-tune for medical images

**How it worked:**
- Input: medical images (X-rays, scans)
- ResNet50 extracts features through convolutional layers
- Final layer classifies into medical categories
- Output: classification label + confidence score
- This contributed to the 96.85% accuracy figure

**Interview prep:**
- *"What is a CNN?"* → Neural network specialized for image data. Uses convolutional filters to detect spatial patterns. Stacks of conv + pooling + fully-connected layers
- *"What is a residual connection?"* → A shortcut that lets input bypass one or more layers, added to the output. Helps train very deep networks by preventing vanishing gradients
- *"Why not use a Vision Transformer (ViT)?"* → ViTs need more training data. ResNet50 works well with smaller medical datasets and our compute budget

