### 3.8 BioBERT (Drug-Drug Interaction)

> [!info] What BERT is
> Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers. A pretrained language model that understands text context in both directions (left and right).

> [!info] What BioBERT is
> BERT pretrained on biomedical text (PubMed abstracts + PMC full-text articles). Better at understanding medical terminology than vanilla BERT.

**Why BioBERT for Care++:**
- Medical text has specialized vocabulary (drug names, conditions, dosages)
- BioBERT was pretrained on 18B biomedical words → understands this vocabulary
- Strong at biomedical Named Entity Recognition (NER) — identifying drugs, diseases, symptoms
- Can be fine-tuned for drug-drug interaction (DDI) classification

**How used in Care++:**
- Input: pairs of drug names + clinical context
- BioBERT extracts contextual embeddings
- Classification head predicts: does drug A interact with drug B?
- Output: interaction risk + severity

**Interview prep:**
- *"Why BioBERT over GPT?"* → Specialized for biomedical NER and classification. GPT is generative (good for free-form text). BioBERT is encoder-only, better for classification tasks like DDI prediction
- *"What is NER?"* → Named Entity Recognition — identifying and classifying named entities in text (drug name, disease, symptom, etc.)
- *"How is BioBERT trained?"* → Pretrained on biomedical text using masked language modeling. Then fine-tuned on specific tasks like DDI

