### 3.9 LLM (Llama / Llama-3) — Clinical Summarization

> [!info] What an LLM is
> Large Language Model — a transformer-based neural network with billions of parameters, trained on massive text data. Generates text via next-token prediction.

> [!info] What Llama is
> Meta's open-source LLM family. Llama-3 is the third generation, with strong reasoning and instruction-following.

**Why Llama-3 for Care++:**
- Open-source → can run on-prem (privacy for medical data)
- Strong instruction-following → good for structured summarization
- Available in multiple sizes (8B, 70B) for different compute budgets
- No API costs

**How used in Care++:**
- Input: long clinical notes, lab reports
- Output: structured summary highlighting key findings, diagnoses, recommendations
- Used **prompt templates** to ensure consistent output format
- Output was structured JSON for frontend consumption

**Interview prep:**
- *"Why Llama-3 over GPT-4?"* → Open-source = privacy + no API costs. Medical data is sensitive, can't go to OpenAI. Llama can run on-prem.
- *"Did you train Llama-3?"* → No, used pretrained weights and just engineered prompts. Training an LLM requires massive GPU resources we didn't have.
- *"How did you handle hallucinations?"* → Carefully designed prompt templates instructing the model to only summarize provided context. Temperature was kept low (around 0-0.3) for factual outputs. (NOTE: don't claim RAG was used — paper doesn't mention it)

