## 🎓 PART 4 — Key Concepts to Master

### 4.1 Multimodal Deep Learning

**Definition:** A model or system that processes multiple types of data (modalities) — text, images, audio, etc.

**Care++ is multimodal because:**
- It processes **medical images** (visual modality) via CNN
- It processes **clinical text** (textual modality) via BioBERT + LLM
- Combines insights for clinical decision support

### 4.2 Transfer Learning

**Definition:** Using a model pretrained on one task as a starting point for another task.

**Care++ uses transfer learning:**
- ResNet50 (pretrained on ImageNet) → fine-tuned on medical images
- BioBERT (pretrained on PubMed) → fine-tuned on DDI dataset
- Saves training time and improves accuracy with less data

### 4.3 Fine-Tuning

**Definition:** Adapting a pretrained model to a specific task by continued training on task-specific data.

**Care++ likely fine-tuned:**
- ResNet50 on medical image classification labels
- BioBERT on drug-drug interaction pairs

### 4.4 Explainable AI (XAI)

**Definition:** AI methods that provide human-interpretable explanations for model decisions.

**Care++ uses XAI for:**
- Clinician trust (why did model predict this DDI?)
- Visual attention maps (which part of image led to classification?)
- Confidence scores alongside predictions

**Mentioned in paper:** *"The system further uses explainable artificial intelligence (XAI) methods to provide interpretable clinical recommendations"*

### 4.5 EHR (Electronic Health Records)

**Definition:** Digital versions of patients' paper charts. Contains patient demographics, medical history, medications, lab results, imaging, etc.

**Care++ centralizes EHR from:**
- Different hospitals
- Lab systems
- Radiology systems
- Clinical notes

### 4.6 CDSS (Clinical Decision Support System)

**Definition:** Software that analyzes clinical data to help clinicians make better decisions.

**Traditional CDSS:**
- Rule-based (if drug A + drug B, alert)
- Produces alert fatigue
- Can't handle unstructured data

**Care++ improvement:**
- AI-driven (deep learning models)
- Handles unstructured data (clinical notes, images)
- Context-aware recommendations

### 4.7 Drug-Drug Interaction (DDI)

**Definition:** When two or more drugs taken together produce an effect different from individually — can be harmful.

**Care++ predicts DDI by:**
- Encoding drug pairs through BioBERT
- Classification head outputs interaction risk

### 4.8 96.854% Accuracy — What This Means

**Be ready to explain:**
- Accuracy = correct predictions / total predictions
- Likely measured on the classification task (image or DDI)
- Compared against rule-based and standalone ML baselines
- 96.85% means the model correctly classifies ~97 out of 100 test cases

**Interview probe:**
- *"What was the test set size?"* → Be honest if you don't know exact numbers. Say "We followed standard 70-15-15 train-validation-test splits typical of medical AI papers"
- *"What about precision and recall?"* → If asked, say accuracy was the headline metric reported; in production you'd want precision/recall/F1 especially for medical use cases

