## 🎤 PART 5 — Common Interview Questions (Master These)

### Q1: Walk me through Care++ end-to-end (2 minutes)

**Model answer:**
> Care++ is a unified patient health record and AI-powered clinical decision support system. The problem we tackled is that healthcare data is fragmented across hospitals, labs, and systems — clinicians often miss critical context, leading to wrong diagnoses or dangerous drug prescriptions.
>
> Our solution has three layers. A React web app for clinicians and a Flutter app for patients sit on top. The Spring Boot backend handles authentication, EHR management, and business logic, talking to a PostgreSQL database. The Spring Boot service also calls a Flask AI microservice written in Python.
>
> The AI microservice hosts three deep learning components — a ResNet50 CNN for medical image classification, BioBERT for biomedical NER and drug-drug interaction prediction, and an LLM (Llama-3) for clinical summarization. Each model returns structured outputs that the Spring Boot layer aggregates and serves to the frontend.
>
> We achieved 96.85% classification accuracy and published the work as IEEE research at RMKMATE 2026.

### Q2: What was your specific contribution?

**Honest answer:**
> Care++ was a team project with four members. I primarily led the full-stack integration — Spring Boot backend services, JWT-based RBAC, REST contracts between the backend and the AI service, and the React web interface. The AI model implementation — fine-tuning ResNet50 and BioBERT, prompt engineering for Llama — was a collaborative effort across the team. We all contributed to writing the paper.

### Q3: Why did you use a microservices architecture?

> Two main reasons. First, the AI layer is Python-heavy (PyTorch, Hugging Face) and the backend is Java-heavy (Spring Boot, JPA). Splitting them along language boundaries was natural. Second, we wanted independent scaling — the AI service might need GPU resources while the backend just needs CPU. Microservices let us scale them separately and isolate failures.

### Q4: Why BioBERT specifically for DDI?

> Medical text has highly specialized vocabulary that general-purpose BERT doesn't handle well. BioBERT was pretrained on 18 billion biomedical words from PubMed and PMC, so it understands medical terminology — drug names, conditions, dosages. For drug-drug interaction classification, this contextual understanding gives much better results than vanilla BERT or word2vec approaches.

### Q5: How did you handle medical data privacy?

> Several layers. JWT-based authentication with role-based access control — clinicians, patients, and admins have different permission scopes. Encrypted connections (HTTPS / TLS). Audit logging on sensitive operations. PostgreSQL row-level security where applicable. And we kept the LLM (Llama) on-premise — we didn't use OpenAI or any external API for medical data, which was a deliberate design choice for compliance.

### Q6: Why ResNet50 over a Vision Transformer?

> Vision Transformers typically need much more training data and compute than CNNs. ResNet50 is a proven architecture for medical imaging, has strong pretrained weights from ImageNet, and works well with the smaller medical datasets typically available in academic work. The residual connections also make training stable. We optimized for what works reliably with our resources.

### Q7: How did you avoid hallucinations in the LLM summarization?

> We used carefully designed prompt templates that instruct the model to only use the provided context and explicitly say "I don't have enough information" rather than fabricate. We kept temperature low (around 0-0.3) for factual outputs. And we made the LLM output structured JSON, which constrains what it can say. For high-stakes clinical outputs, we also included human review in the loop — clinicians could see the source data alongside the summary.

> [!warning] DO NOT mention RAG in this answer
> The paper doesn't claim RAG was used. Don't introduce RAG as a Care++ feature in any interview answer.

### Q8: What is explainable AI and how did you use it?

> Explainable AI (XAI) is a set of methods that make model decisions interpretable to humans. In Care++, this matters because clinicians need to trust why the AI flagged a drug interaction or classified an image a certain way. We used techniques like attention visualization for BioBERT (showing which parts of the text influenced the DDI prediction) and class activation maps for ResNet50 (showing which regions of an image led to classification). This builds clinician trust and meets the regulatory expectation of model interpretability in healthcare.

### Q9: What is transfer learning?

> Transfer learning is when you take a model pretrained on one task and adapt it to a different but related task. In Care++, we used ResNet50 pretrained on ImageNet (everyday images) and fine-tuned it on medical images — letting it transfer its low-level feature detection (edges, shapes) while learning medical-specific patterns. Same with BioBERT pretrained on PubMed text, fine-tuned for DDI classification. Transfer learning saves huge amounts of training time and works well with smaller domain-specific datasets.

### Q10: What would you improve if you continued?

> A few things. One, add a proper RAG pipeline over medical literature to ground LLM summaries — currently the LLM works from clinical notes alone. Two, add formal evaluation metrics beyond accuracy — precision, recall, F1, and ideally clinical safety metrics. Three, deploy with Kubernetes and add proper observability with Prometheus/Grafana. Four, build out the patient mobile app more — Flutter was a good start but the feature set was limited. Five, integrate with HL7 FHIR for true interoperability with existing hospital systems.

### Q11: How is the IEEE paper structured?

> Standard format. Introduction motivates the problem of healthcare data fragmentation. Literature survey reviews existing CDSS work and identifies gaps. Proposed System describes the architecture and AI components. Result section reports the 96.85% classification accuracy and comparison against baselines. Conclusion summarizes the contribution.

### Q12: Are you the first author?

> No, I'm one of four authors on the paper. It was a team research project — Deepa R, Jagdish E, Hemanath U, and myself. I contributed primarily on the full-stack engineering side while the team collaborated on AI implementation and writing.

